{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603130"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:34:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:34:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.63,0.1,0.23,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82190"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67388"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8581"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82190"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe zona pellucida is a critical structure in mammalian reproduction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the zona pellucida?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A cellular layer derived from the cumulus oophorus","A glycoprotein layer containing sperm-binding proteins ZP1-4","A lipid bilayer surrounding the corona radiata","A protein barrier produced by granulosa cells after fertilisation","A temporary structure that dissolves during meiosis I"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglycoprotein layer containing sperm-binding proteins ZP1-4\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct description of the zona pellucida. This extracellular matrix surrounds the plasma membrane of mammalian oocytes and early embryos. The zona proteins are crucial for species-specific sperm binding and preventing polyspermy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elipid bilayer surrounding the corona radiata\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the zona pellucida is made of glycoproteins, not lipids, and lies beneath the corona radiata. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotein barrier produced by granulosa cells after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the zona pellucida is present before fertilisation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporary structure that dissolves during meiosis I\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the zona pellucida persists through fertilisation and early embryonic development. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecellular layer derived from the cumulus oophorus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the zona pellucida is acellular and is secreted by the oocyte itself.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The zona pellucida is a glycoprotein layer surrounding the oocyte that contains sperm-binding proteins ZP1-4","The zona pellucida prevents polyspermy through the cortical reaction","The zona pellucida maintains species-specificity in fertilisation"],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Fortune JE, Yang MY, Muruvi W. The earliest stages of follicular development: follicle formation and activation. Soc Reprod Fertil Suppl. 2010;67:203-16. doi: 10.7313/upo9781907284991.018. PMID: 21755674; PMCID: PMC5316466","Zhang T, He M, Zhang J, Tong Y, Chen T, Wang C, Pan W, Xiao Z. Mechanisms of primordial follicle activation and new pregnancy opportunity for premature ovarian failure patients. Front Physiol. 2023 Feb 28;14:1113684. doi: 10.3389/fphys.2023.1113684. PMID: 36926197; PMCID: PMC10011087","Oliver R, Pillarisetty LS. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Ovary Corpus Luteum. [Updated 2023 Jan 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539704/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67388"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67388"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-28T17:28:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-28T17:29:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8408"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82190"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"c